%I A396960 #12 Jun 18 2026 16:38:04
%S A396960 1,2,4,8,9,16,17,18,32,34,36,64,68,72,128,136,144,145,256,272,273,288,
%T A396960 290,512,544,546,576,580,1024,1088,1092,1152,1160,1165,2048,2176,2184,
%U A396960 2304,2320,2321,2330,4096,4352,4368,4369,4608,4640,4642,4660
%N A396960 Conjectured list of numbers whose trajectory under the 15x+1 map eventually reaches 1, where the map sends odd x to 15x+1 and even x to x/2.
%C A396960 The 15x+1 analog of A267703 (which treats the 7x+1 map). Here 15 = 2^4 - 1 is a Mersenne number, and 15*1 + 1 = 16 = 2^4, so 1 lies on the cycle 1 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1.
%C A396960 "Conjectured" in the same sense as A267703: every term shown provably reaches 1, but it is conjectural that the numbers not shown never do (a trajectory might in principle descend after exceeding the search bound).
%C A396960 Terms were computed by exact backward-tree enumeration from 1 (preimages of v are 2*v, and (v-1)/15 when that is an odd integer > 1) with excursion bound 10^16; the list is unchanged at bounds 10^17 and 10^18 and is certified complete below 10^16 under that bound.
%C A396960 The sequence is infinite: it contains A131865, since 15*(16^(j+1)-1)/15 + 1 = 16^(j+1) is a power of 2. If k is a term, then so is 2*k. All powers of 2 are terms.
%C A396960 Almost all positive integers diverge under this map (Heppner 1978); the present sequence has density 0.
%C A396960 The number of terms <= X appears to grow like X^c with c ~= 0.1310, where c is the maximum over b of (H(b) - b*L)/(1 - b*L) with L = log2(15) and H the binary entropy function (conjectural). There are 57, 87, 123, 182 terms <= 10^4, 10^5, 10^6, 10^7 respectively.
%H A396960 Karan Sharma, <a href="/A396960/b396960.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..182</a>
%H A396960 E. Heppner, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01226454">Eine Bemerkung zum Hasse-Syracuse-Algorithmus</a>, Arch. Math. 31 (1978), 317-320.
%e A396960 9 is a term: 9 -> 136 -> 68 -> 34 -> 17 -> 256 -> 128 -> 64 -> 32 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1.
%e A396960 3 is (conjecturally) not a term: 3 -> 46 -> 23 -> 346 -> 173 -> 2596 -> ... appears to grow without ever reaching 1.
%o A396960 (Python)
%o A396960 def aupto(lim, bound=10**12):  # bound = excursion cap, must far exceed lim
%o A396960     seen, todo = {1}, [1]
%o A396960     for v in todo:  # walk the tree of preimages of 1
%o A396960         kids = [2*v]
%o A396960         if v % 15 == 1 and (v // 15) % 2:  # (v-1)/15 is an odd integer
%o A396960             kids.append(v // 15)
%o A396960         for u in kids:
%o A396960             if 1 < u <= bound and u not in seen:
%o A396960                 seen.add(u); todo.append(u)
%o A396960     return sorted(x for x in seen if x <= lim)
%o A396960 print(aupto(10**4))
%Y A396960 Cf. A267703 (7x+1 analog), A131865 (a subsequence: (16^(n+1)-1)/15), A000079 (powers of 2, a subsequence).
%K A396960 nonn
%O A396960 1,2
